{
  "answer": "No work in the corpus offers extended philosophical engagement with fire (*agni*) personified as a ritual sacrament (such as elaborate hymns to Agni as divine mediator or metaphysical analysis of fire's sacramental role). However, numerous Dharmaśāstra texts (Smṛtis) prescribe fire-based rituals—especially the *agnihotra* (twice-daily milk oblation into the sacred fire) and *aupāsana* (domestic hearth fire)—where fire serves as the essential sacramental medium for offerings to deities, ancestors, and other beings, purifying and conveying them supernaturally.[^1][^2][^3] These are obligatory for householders (*gṛhasthins*) maintaining sacred fires (*āhitāgni*). The relevant works, drawn exhaustively from corpus searches, are:\n\n- **Āṅgirasa Smṛti**: Prescribes *aupāsana* fire-offerings and *agnihotra*.[^4]\n- **Bṛhaspati Smṛti**: References merit from performing *agnihotra*.[^5]\n- **Manusmṛti**: Details *agnihotra* duties, equates domestic fires metaphorically to parents/*guru*, and requires it alongside new-/full-moon sacrifices.[^6]\n- **Parāśara Smṛti**: Notes decline of *agnihotra* in Kali Yuga; prescribes it situationally.[^7]\n- **Slokantara**: Lists *agnihotra* fire-offering among futile acts without inner merit.[^8]\n- **Viṣṇu Smṛti**: Mandates morning/evening *agnihotra*.[^9]\n- **Vīramitrodaya**: Extensively discusses *agnihotra* superseding fasts, its *śrauta* priority, and ritual details.[^10]\n\nOther Smṛtis (e.g., Kātyāyana, Yama, Yājñavalkya, Nārada) likely reference these rituals based on genre conventions, but no direct matches appeared in phrase searches. Non-Indic works (Old English poems, Urdu ghazals, French treatises) show no such engagement.\n\n[^1]: Manusmṛti treats fire as the purifying conduit for oblations (*Manusmṛti*, [Chapter 4](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/04/translation/#p-8b8ea4)).\n\n[^2]: Āṅgirasa Smṛti on *agnihotra* penalties (*Āṅgirasa Smṛti*, [Chapter 1](/works/unknown-angirasa-smrti-2bf9d1/01/translation/#p-063dc6)).\n\n[^3]: Vīramitrodaya prioritizes *śrauta* *agnihotra* over *smārta* fasts (*Vīramitrodaya*, [Chapter 1](/works/unknown-viramitrodaya-d4b632/01/translation/#p-8cf8de)).\n\n[^4]: *Āṅgirasa Smṛti*, [Chapter 1](/works/unknown-angirasa-smrti-2bf9d1/01/translation/#p-00ce10).\n\n[^5]: *Bṛhaspati Smṛti*, [Chapter 1](/works/unknown-brhaspati-smrti-0fd070/01/translation/#p-bd8c79).\n\n[^6]: *Manusmṛti*, [Chapter 4](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/04/translation/#p-8b8ea4); also Chapter 2 on *garhapatya* fire (*Manusmṛti*, [Chapter 2](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/02/translation/#p-3e3f4a)).\n\n[^7]: *Parāśara Smṛti*, [Chapter 1](/works/unknown-parasara-smrti-2259be/01/translation/#p-8153d5).\n\n[^8]: *Slokantara*, [Chapter 1](/works/unknown-slokantara-d7a628/01/translation/#p-243b40).\n\n[^9]: *Viṣṇu Smṛti*, [Chapter 59](/works/unknown-visnu-smrti-27f0d8/59/translation/#p-9eea18).\n\n[^10]: *Vīramitrodaya*, [Chapter 1](/works/unknown-viramitrodaya-d4b632/01/translation/#p-8cf8de).",
